mcafee@netcom.com (McAfee Associates) writes:

>     Three new viruses have appeared in the past two months that
> utilize the Bulgarian Dark Avenger Mutation Engine.  The source
> code for this mutation engine has appeared on numerous virus-
> exchange bulletin boards and is now in the hands of virus writers.

The source?! Are you sure? What we have here is a virus development
kit, which contains the MtE as a compiled, ready to link OBJ file,
together with a demo virus in source. As far as I know, the source of
the MtE itself has not been made available.

> The source code can be compiled and linked with any .COM file-
> infecting virus, thus making the virus undetectable to any string-
> based scanning technique.

A slight correction. You cannot just take an existing old virus and
make it polymorphic with the MtE. You need to modify it first, in
order to make it MtE-aware. This requires the source of the virus, or
at least an assemblable disassembly.

>      Since stealth viruses and other viruses designed to avoid
> filter- or CRC-checking- type anti-virus programs can be altered
> using the mutation engine, this poses a real threat to current
> security systems.  If a virus is specifically designed to avoid
> memory-resident filters, and also cannot be caught by a scanner,
> then there will be no protection against it.

C'mon, let's be serious. There is no such virus against which there is
no protection. Any integrity checker that is worth the price of the
disk space it occupies will detect any polymorphic virus, including
the ones produced with the MtE. Of course, the MtE poses some problems
to the scanners.

