Date:    Thu, 26 Mar 92 00:31:06 +0000
From:    wales@CS.UCLA.EDU (Rich Wales)
Subject: Re: Stacker and viruses (PC)

I wrote the following a few days ago:

	As I've said above, there is no reason to avoid Stacker
	or other compressing disk drivers out of concern over
	viral infection.

Vesselin Bontchev replied:

	Consider a virus which randomly overwrites sectors of the
	hard disk (e.g., Dark_Avenger.1800.Standard).  Suppose
	that it does the damage before Stacker's device driver is
	loaded (or alternatively, does the damage to the drive on
	which the large stacked file can be seen).  Overwriting
	just ONE sector of the file which contains the stacked
	volume will damage the whole volume - just like damaging
	a few bytes in the middle of a ZIP archive damages the
	whole archive.

Based on the understanding I have of how Stacker works, the above
isn't quite correct.

Stacker does =not= take your entire disk and create one huge ZIP-like
archive file out of it.  Instead, it takes "clusters" or "allocation
units" and compresses each of these separately and individually.  If
you consider that Stacker is supposed to be 99.9% transparent to DOS
(and thus must permit random disk access, including random access to
individual files of arbitrary length), you'll quickly realize that
this is the only way a compressing disk driver such as Stacker can
work.

In order to get better compression, by the way, a Stacker volume is
normally set up with a cluster size of 8K bytes (instead of the
2K-byte cluster size that is normal with hard drives).  The compressed
version of each 8K-byte data block is then stored as zero or more
512-byte sec- tors on the disk.  Stacker maintains its own map of
where each block is stored.

Now, if a virus such as Dark Avenger scribbles on a random sector
some- where within a Stacker volume, this will mess up the compressed
copy of some 8K-byte cluster -- but it won't automatically ruin the
whole drive.

Of course, if the nuked sector happens to have been holding something
critical, you could be in serious trouble.  To some extent, to be
sure, this kind of thing could happen with a non-Stacker disk
partition as well -- though (as Vesselin pointed out to me via e-mail)
a virus might be smart enough to avoid smashing the FAT or root
directory of a regular DOS partition, but not smart enough to avoid
doing comparable damage to a Stacker volume.

So, I stand by my earlier claim that compressing disk drivers such as
Stacker need not be avoided by people who are concerned about the pos-
sible effect of a virus.

