Date:    Thu, 26 Mar 92 14:52:00 +1200
From:    "Mark Aitchison, U of Canty; Physics" <PHYS169@csc.canterbury.ac.nz>
Subject: Re: Is this a virus? (PC)

VANCLEEF@MPS.OHIO-STATE.EDU writes:
> Last night I was working on my 286 AT clone at home, when I did a
> command which corresponds to an executable in a utilities directory in
> my search path, and my machine responded with 'bad command or file
> does not exist' error message. I thought this was curious, to I went
> to the directory and did a 'dir' and got a list of some files, and
> then followed by a bunch of garbed junk! This was repeatable every
> time I tried to look at the directory (and all directories it turned
> out)!
>
> I rebooted the machine and then the problem went away. Has anyone out
> there seen this problem? I used SCAN and it didn't detect any thing.
> Any clues?

It may or may not be a virus. What has happened is that the RAM copy
of some or all of your disk (directory) contents has gone amiss.  This
could be due to some conflict between cache software (or DOS loaded
high) and some other software, or a flakey (or temperature-sensitive)
disk, or a virus.  You should:

(1) Run a couple of good scanners on the system (boot from a clean diskette!)
(2) Try to remember what software you ran just before the fault showed up,
    and try running it again.
(3) If something like that occurs again, don't write anything to disk (i.e.
    don't add/delete/rename files, sort directories, edit files, etc), but
    look around to see if any other directories are affected.  You can use
    CHKDSK, but NOT WITH THE /F option.
(4) Run some disk testors, to look for flakey disk problems; Norton's DT is
    barely good enough - try the (shareware?) HDDIAG scanning for defects,
    (not analyze because it wipes the disk!)
(5) Run a heuristic analysis program on at least your hard disk's boot sector
(6) If it occurs again, let me know:
     * What scanners you used
     * If you used F-PROT 2.02's heuristics mode, what it said
     * Your config.sys & autoexec.bat
     * What program(s) you were running just before the problem
     * whether HDDIAG or DT or CHKDSK reported anythinbg wrong with the disk.
    (Some day soon I'll have a program that bundles all of this checking into
    one!).

In general, it is a good idea to at least run a modern virus checker
and some hardware diagnostics on your disk, reporting what they found
(or the fact they didn't find anything) with "Is this a virus?" type
of requests.

Mark Aitchison, Physics, University of Canterbury, New Zealand.

