Date:    26 Mar 92 11:06:12 +0000
From:    bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)
Subject: Re: chkdsk reporting 654336 total memory (PC)

luc.bussieres@dmi.usherb.ca (Luc Bussieres) writes:

> [Moderator's note: Added to FAQ.]

OK, so here's the FAA (Frequently Answered Answers)... :-)

> 	When I run chkdsk on several pc it is reporting 654336 total
> memory instead of the 655... that it is usually reporting. I then

A missing 1 Kb might by caused by:

1) A PS/2 computer. The PS/2 computers are set up this way for unknown
reasons. Maybe someone from IBM can comment on this.

2) A computer with American Megatrends Inc. (AMI) BIOS, which is set
up (with the built-in CMOS setup program) in such a way that the BIOS
uses the upper 1 Kb of the memory for its internal variables. It can
be instructed to use the lower memory instead. You have to play a bit
with the setup program (press <Del> while rebooting in order to invoce
it).

3) DOS 5.0 loaded high. It "steals" 16 bytes (one MCB descriptor) from
the upper part of the conventional memory. Since some memory snoopers
report the amount of memory in whole kilobytes, they'll report that
only 639 Kb are available in this case. In fact, it is 640 Kb - 16
bytes.

4) Some special customary BIOSes. I have seen a laptop with 3 Kb
missing. The BIOS used them for a built-in callendar and calculator.

5) A SCSI controller. Some of them "steal" one Kb from the top of the
conventional memory.

6) If you have a 386/ix installed and boot from its partition. I know
nothing about 386/ix, but I received a MBR from a user, who reported 1
Kb missing and I discovered that he's booting from the 386/ix
partition.

7) A memory resident virus.

> decided to run scan version 86 on those pc from a clean floppy and it
> is detecting no viruses. Is it possible that it is a new virus that is
> unknown from McAffee scan ?

The scanners (including McAfee's VIRUSCAN) are able to detect only
known viruses and minor modifications of them. Therefore, if it is a
new virus, SCAN won't detect it for sure. Try booting from a
non-infected write-protected system diskette. If the 1 Kb is still
missing, then you don't have a virus. If it isn't missing any more, it
might be a virus, or one of the cases above (3, 6). If you can't decide,
send a copy of the master boot sector and the boot sector of the
active partition to an anti-virus researcher.

