Date:    24 Mar 92 21:01:35 -0500
From:    Leonard Erickson <70524.2603@CompuServe.COM>
Subject: Network Viruses

Suresh Thennarangam asks:

>1> Is it possible to bypass the read-only file-locking mechanism
>   provided by Novell Netware and Banyan Vines ?>
>
>2> Is it possible to bypass the read-only file server option in 3COM ?
>
>3> Technically, there ought to be a low-level hack way to achieve
>both, but has anyone come across a virus that does this ?

There's a bit of confusion here.

Under Novell Netware (and I would assume under the other Network OSes)
the read-only attribute is *exactly* the same as that given under DOS.
Thus it is changeable by user software.

BUT... If a user doesn't have "Modify" rights in the directory (or to
the files under Netware 3.x) he cannot change the flag.

Likewise, if you do not have Write or Erase access to a
file/directory, you cannot change the files there. No virus running on
the PC can change this, as all the access to those files is via calls
to the Netware OS WHICH IS NOT MS-DOS COMPATIBLE.

A virus has to *ask* permission like any other program, and if Netware
has been told to deny it, that's all she wrote. Netware isn't
infectable via the LAN, only via running software on the *physical*
machine that is the server.

The one exception to this is if someone with Supervisor rights runs
something infected. But even then, it is possible to protect the files
to some extent. (for example, if a COM or EXE file is flagged 'execute
only' NO ONE can change it, not even the supervisor. It cannot be
read, only executed or deleted)

We once had a virus get loose on a few PCs attached to the network.
The infect only spread to a few files because the users didn't have
Write privileges in most directories that contained executables.

On the other hand, practically *everything* on their local HD was
infected.

While I've spoken of Novell above, I'd think that most of the other
LAN OSes out there should have similar protections.

